The number of Rhino (Gaidas) in Nepal stood at 612 in 2000. Nepal has been successful in virtually eliminating poaching of this endangered species which should spell good news for the overall numbers, however the significant number of rhino deaths since July 2018, in and around Chitwan National Park, creates uncertainty as to the actual number that will be counted in the census.

Much focus is given to the population of near extict big mammal species (more then the recovery of ecosystems worldwide, which should be the focus). However: Nepal is lacking a good infrastructure to realize this.

Going for the middle

The government has budgeted for the 2020 census which is the first time they have done so. They traditionally relied on donations from international organizations, however, due to the greater than average losses of rhinos over the last two years, they have taken decisive action.

If the growth rate from the last two census are anything to go by we would be looking at a population of 750+. However, it has been well documented that there has been a spike in rhino fatalities in Nepal, so a continuation of past growth rates seems unlikely.

A civil war from 1996-2006 makes it difficult to compare figures before 2011.[1] For example, in 2002, poachers killed 37 rhinos.[2] But, we have average rates of deaths for unknown or natural causes for the current period: "Between 2004 and 2014, a total of 81 rhinos died from unknown or natural causes — an average of around seven per year. That number has since shot up: From 2015 to 2017, 60 such deaths were recorded, an average of 20 per year."[3] Let's assume that poaching is low single digits over the period.

The key issues to answer this question are the following:

This question need to clear up live, and dead animals ? The animals that are alive so, which are we counting? The government announcement comes as significant numbers of Nepal’s rhinos have been dying due to unknown or natural causes. Since mid-July 2018, 45 rhinos have been found dead in and around Chitwan National Park, the country’s main rhino sanctuary.

From 2015-fiscal year 2019 (July in Nepal), 108 rhinos died, mostly from natural causes. This would take the 645 counted in 2015 down to 537, before rhino births and not accounting for unreported deaths + deaths this year. (1)

Trying to round up somebody who knows about this since I don't know anybody in the Nepalese government any more. Meanwhile, the next time the right wing of the GOP conducts a RINO census, they will probably need to count me.

Very rough estimate of change in rhino population since April 2015: Change in population = A (Surviving births) - B (Deaths) A. Surviving births estimate: Rhino population at April 2015 = 645 No. female rhinos estimate -> 320 (50% of total) No. female rhinos aged at least 6 years (typical minimum breeding age in wild) estimate = -> 272 (85% of total) Each breeding-age female rhino tends to produce 1 calf every 3-5 years -> between 272 and 450 births between April 2015 and April 2020: however... Infant mortality rate for rhinos in wild = 12% -> no. survivors -> between 240 and 396 Assume some % of breeding population does not reproduce, for whatever reason -> reduce no. survivors to somewhere between 190-320 (if 20% non-reproducing) and 215-350 (if 10% non-reproducing) [https://news.mongabay.com/2019/10/at-indias-assam-zoo-decades-of-experience-lead-to-rhino-breeding-success/] https://www.nationalgeographic.com/animals/mammals/i/indian-rhinoceros/ . Deaths estimate: Most recent year: minimum of 45 deaths Previous year: minimum of 30 deaths (assume this holds for the previous years since 2015) -> 165 minimum over 5 years Scale up for deaths not detected/reported -> 180 deaths (10% error margin), 200 deaths (20% error margin) https://thehimalayantimes.com/nepal/one-rhino-dies-every-eight-days-in-chitwan-national-park/ Overall change: suggests numbers should have held up. Best possible scenario would be an increase of around 170. Worst possible would be a modest decrease. These are very tentative numbers. (Perhaps the overall surviving births number has been brought down by lower reproduction rates or higher calf mortality rates than the historic averages, arising from e.g. pressure on resources, adverse weather conditions etc. However it's hard to see the outcome being much better than the best case scenario as birth rates are subject to biological constraints...) Next question: if anything less than the best case scenario is the result of the census, would the government allow its publication given they have announced a doubling in population over the last decade? I find this even harder to predict than rhino population rates. Given the scale of the exercise it seems like it would be difficult but not impossible to find a pretext to suppress publication. However, it might be easier simply to publish and to point to a factor like the 2017 floods to explain a disappointing outcome.
